I don't love this topic but it's important that I talk about it because I have concerns about the use of glyphosate -- it's impact on humans, gut microbes, the environment, and occupational exposures. The IARC labels glyphosate a probable human carcinogen while the EPA says it is "not likely to be carcinogenic to humans." Confusing, except "the EPA relied mostly on registrant-commissioned, unpublished regulatory studies, 99% of which were negative, while IARC relied mostly on peer-reviewed studies of which 70% were positive (83 of 118)." Eeek! I don't like that. To each their own, but I personally choose to buy organic wheat, corn, soy and oats because if it's organic it can't be sprayed with this chemical. There are many studies... Too many cite, but here are a few mostly gut biome ones: PMID: 26883814; 31442459; 29635013; 35629374; 33547360; 34543792; 35356729 ... could keep going. I hope we have more transparent, honest, non-industry funded research in the future to expand our understanding on this topic. Meanwhile, I'll be choosing the side of caution. #fiberfueled #guthealth #gutdoctor #healthandwellness #glyphosate

Seagrasses are indicator species for environmental issues. Because they respond rapidly to environmental change, they provide insights into overfishing and destructive fishing practices, pollution and water quality, and much more. This year our partner for planet ocean is Project Seagrass, their vision: A world in which seagrass meadows are thriving, abundant and well managed for people and planet. Seagrass meadows are among the most common coastal habitats on Earth, covering at leastÂ 266,562 km2 Â in at least 136 countries. They nurture fish populations, weaken storm surges, and provide numerous other services to coastal communities. Seagrass ecosystems are biologically rich and highly productive, providing valuable nursery habitats to more than 20 per cent of the worldâ€™s largest 25 fisheries. They can filter pathogens, bacteria, and pollution out of seawater, and are home to endangered and charismatic species such as dugongs, seahorses, and sea turtles. But an estimated 1-2 per cent of seagrass habitat is being lost worldwide each year, and a number of the worldâ€™s 72 seagrass species are in decline. Since the late 19th century, almost 20 per cent of known seagrass area across the globe has been lost. Reversing this trend is possible.
